Can AI spot Alzheimer's from brain scans without sharing patient data?
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Researchers tested 6 ways to teach a computer to tell if a person has Alzheimer&rsquo;s disease&mdash;just by looking at brain scans.&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; They used scans from two hospitals: Hospital A (428 patients) and Hospital B (360 patients).&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; The big question: Which method gives the best result while keeping patient information 100% private?&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;
How Each Method Scored




Method
Hospital A Score
Hospital B Score




Cross (Worst)
81.8%
81.1%


Single
84.4%
82.8%


Mix (Illegal)
87.0%
87.2%


FedAvg
86.0%
84.2%


FedSGD
82.3%
84.4%


FedProx
85.8%
85.6%



&nbsp;
What Each Method Does&nbsp;
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Cross &mdash; The worst method: Teach the computer using only Hospital A&rsquo;s scans, then test it on Hospital B without any changes. The scans from the two hospitals look different (like a selfie vs. a professional photo). The computer gets confused and makes many mistakes.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;

💡 Real life example: Learning to ride a bicycle, then being asked to ride a motorcycle without any practice.
&nbsp; &nbsp;
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Single &mdash; Each hospital works alone: Hospital A trains and tests only on its own scans. Hospital B does the same. No sharing. Better than Cross because the test scans match the training scans, but each hospital has few patients, so the AI is not very smart.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Real life example: Two teachers who never talk to each other &mdash; each only sees their own students&rsquo; work.&nbsp; &nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Mix &mdash; Best but illegal: Put all scans from both hospitals into one big pile and train the computer on everything. This gives the best result (~87% correct). But sharing real patient scans is against privacy laws (like HIPAA). Cannot be used in real hospitals.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Real life example: Taking every student&rsquo;s answer sheet to make a perfect answer key &mdash; great result, but breaks all privacy rules.&nbsp; &nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; FedAvg &mdash; Best legal method (no data sharing): Each hospital trains its own AI locally &mdash; the scans never leave the hospital. Then they only share the &ldquo;recipe&rdquo; (a set of numbers, called weights) with a central computer. The central computer averages all the recipes and sends back a better one.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;
Real life example: Chefs cooking at home. They share only their recipes (not the actual food). A head chef combines them into one master recipe.
&nbsp; &nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; FedSGD &mdash; A weaker version: Similar to FedAvg, but instead of sharing the final recipe, hospitals share tiny, messy step‑by‑step changes. Combining many noisy steps is harder and gives worse results.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;
Real life example: Sharing every pencil stroke you made while solving a math problem, instead of just the final answer.&nbsp; &nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; FedProx &mdash; Like FedAvg, but with a safety rule: Same as FedAvg, but it adds a simple rule: &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t stray too far from the group recipe.&rdquo; This stops one hospital with unusual data from pulling the shared AI in the wrong direction.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;
Real life example: Same chefs, but now they are told: &ldquo;Keep your recipe close to the group template.&rdquo; One overconfident chef can&rsquo;t ruin the whole thing.
&nbsp; &nbsp;
&nbsp;
The 4 Main Takeaways
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;

Mixing all data gives the best score, but it&rsquo;s illegal. You cannot move patient scans between hospitals. This method only shows the maximum possible result.


Using the same AI on a different hospital&rsquo;s scans without any changes is the worst idea. Scanners are different, so the AI fails badly.


FedAvg and FedProx get almost the same high score as Mix, but without sharing data. Only 1% less accuracy, but 100% privacy. That&rsquo;s the big win.

&nbsp;

Sharing final recipes (weights) works much better than step-by-step notes (gradients). The final recipe is stable; the tiny steps are noisy.

&nbsp; &nbsp;
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; In short: wecan say thatb Hospitals can work together to build a very good AI for Alzheimer&rsquo;s detection&mdash;as if they had pooled all their scans&mdash;without ever letting a single patient image leave the building. The small drop in accuracy (only about 1%) is a tiny price for keeping everything private.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;
